{"paragraphs":[{"cues":[{"time":487,"text":"So in my free time outside of Twitter"},{"time":3076,"text":"I experiment a little bit"},{"time":4527,"text":"with telling stories online, experimenting"},{"time":7150,"text":"with what we can do with new digital tools."},{"time":9573,"text":"And in my job at Twitter,"},{"time":11079,"text":"I actually spent a little bit of time"},{"time":12695,"text":"working with authors and storytellers as well,"},{"time":15439,"text":"helping to expand out the bounds"},{"time":17644,"text":"of what people are experimenting with."},{"time":19954,"text":"And I want to talk through some examples today"},{"time":22324,"text":"of things that people have done"},{"time":23733,"text":"that I think are really fascinating"},{"time":25902,"text":"using flexible identity and anonymity on the web"},{"time":29037,"text":"and blurring the lines between fact and fiction."}]},{"cues":[{"time":33110,"text":"But I want to start and go back to the 1930s."},{"time":35262,"text":"Long before a little thing called Twitter,"},{"time":37573,"text":"radio brought us broadcasts"},{"time":40614,"text":"and connected millions of people"},{"time":43498,"text":"to single points of broadcast."},{"time":45939,"text":"And from those single points emanated stories."},{"time":49961,"text":"Some of them were familiar stories."},{"time":51950,"text":"Some of them were new stories."},{"time":53415,"text":"And for a while they were familiar formats,"},{"time":56414,"text":"but then radio began to evolve its own"},{"time":58635,"text":"unique formats specific to that medium."},{"time":61566,"text":"Think about episodes that happened live on radio."}]},{"cues":[{"time":65250,"text":"Combining the live play"},{"time":67573,"text":"and the serialization of written fiction,"},{"time":69934,"text":"you get this new format."},{"time":72119,"text":"And the reason why I bring up radio is that I think"},{"time":74048,"text":"radio is a great example of how a new medium"},{"time":78173,"text":"defines new formats which then define new stories."}]},{"cues":[{"time":81980,"text":"And of course, today, we have an entirely new"},{"time":84916,"text":"medium to play with,"},{"time":86517,"text":"which is this online world."},{"time":87943,"text":"This is the map of verified users on Twitter"},{"time":91807,"text":"and the connections between them."},{"time":93113,"text":"There are thousands upon thousands of them."},{"time":95880,"text":"Every single one of these points"},{"time":97475,"text":"is its own broadcaster."},{"time":99357,"text":"We've gone to this world of many to many,"},{"time":103030,"text":"where access to the tools is the only barrier to broadcasting."},{"time":107795,"text":"And I think that we should start to see"},{"time":110368,"text":"wildly new formats emerge"},{"time":112053,"text":"as people learn how to tell stories in this new medium."},{"time":115961,"text":"I actually believe that we are in a wide open frontier"},{"time":119313,"text":"for creative experimentation, if you will,"},{"time":121501,"text":"that we've explored and begun to settle"},{"time":124850,"text":"this wild land of the Internet"},{"time":126829,"text":"and are now just getting ready"},{"time":129072,"text":"to start to build structures on it,"},{"time":131154,"text":"and those structures are the new formats"},{"time":133241,"text":"of storytelling that the Internet will allow us to create."}]},{"cues":[{"time":137794,"text":"I believe this starts with an evolution"},{"time":140099,"text":"of existing methods."},{"time":141993,"text":"The short story, for example,"},{"time":143756,"text":"people are saying that the short story"},{"time":145218,"text":"is experiencing a renaissance of sorts"},{"time":147993,"text":"thanks to e-readers, digital marketplaces."},{"time":151392,"text":"One writer, Hugh Howey, experimented"},{"time":154470,"text":"with short stories on Amazon"},{"time":156191,"text":"by releasing one very short story called \"Wool.\""},{"time":160723,"text":"And he actually says that he didn't intend"},{"time":163225,"text":"for \"Wool\" to become a series,"},{"time":164570,"text":"but that the audience loved the first story so much"},{"time":167196,"text":"they demanded more, and so he gave them more."},{"time":169607,"text":"He gave them \"Wool 2,\" which was a little bit longer than the first one,"},{"time":173111,"text":"\"Wool 3,\" which was even longer,"},{"time":175105,"text":"culminating in \"Wool 5,\""},{"time":176895,"text":"which was a 60,000-word novel."},{"time":179736,"text":"I think Howey was able to do all of this because"},{"time":183721,"text":"he had the quick feedback system of e-books."},{"time":186664,"text":"He was able to write and publish"},{"time":188466,"text":"in relatively short order."},{"time":190055,"text":"There was no mediator between him and the audience."},{"time":193152,"text":"It was just him directly connected with his audience"},{"time":195958,"text":"and building on the feedback and enthusiasm"},{"time":198107,"text":"that they were giving him."},{"time":199928,"text":"So this whole project was an experiment."},{"time":201813,"text":"It started with the one short story,"},{"time":203920,"text":"and I think the experimentation actually became"},{"time":206049,"text":"a part of Howey's format."},{"time":208377,"text":"And that's something that this medium enabled,"},{"time":211616,"text":"was experimentation being a part of the format itself."}]},{"cues":[{"time":215793,"text":"This is a short story by the author Jennifer Egan"},{"time":218964,"text":"called \"Black Box.\""},{"time":220412,"text":"It was originally written"},{"time":221919,"text":"specifically with Twitter in mind."},{"time":223600,"text":"Egan convinced The New Yorker"},{"time":225909,"text":"to start a New Yorker fiction account"},{"time":228331,"text":"from which they could tweet"},{"time":230148,"text":"all of these lines that she created."},{"time":231952,"text":"Now Twitter, of course, has a 140-character limit."},{"time":235399,"text":"Egan mocked that up just writing manually"},{"time":238240,"text":"in this storyboard sketchbook,"},{"time":241156,"text":"used the physical space constraints"},{"time":244143,"text":"of those storyboard squares"},{"time":245652,"text":"to write each individual tweet,"},{"time":247453,"text":"and those tweets ended up becoming"},{"time":250392,"text":"over 600 of them that were serialized by The New Yorker."},{"time":254080,"text":"Every night, at 8 p.m., you could tune in"},{"time":257850,"text":"to a short story from The New Yorker's fiction account."},{"time":261418,"text":"I think that's pretty exciting:"},{"time":262962,"text":"tune-in literary fiction."},{"time":265468,"text":"The experience of Egan's story, of course,"},{"time":268529,"text":"like anything on Twitter, there were multiple ways to experience it."},{"time":271578,"text":"You could scroll back through it,"},{"time":273117,"text":"but interestingly, if you were watching it live,"},{"time":276000,"text":"there was this suspense that built"},{"time":278631,"text":"because the actual tweets,"},{"time":281148,"text":"you had no control over when you would read them."},{"time":283451,"text":"They were coming at a pretty regular clip,"},{"time":285891,"text":"but as the story was building,"},{"time":288269,"text":"normally, as a reader, you control how fast you move through a text,"},{"time":291512,"text":"but in this case, The New Yorker did,"},{"time":293823,"text":"and they were sending you bit by bit by bit,"},{"time":296993,"text":"and you had this suspense of waiting for the next line."}]},{"cues":[{"time":300275,"text":"Another great example of fiction"},{"time":303346,"text":"and the short story on Twitter,"},{"time":305390,"text":"Elliott Holt is an author who wrote a story called \"Evidence.\""},{"time":308813,"text":"It began with this tweet: \"On November 28"},{"time":311443,"text":"at 10:13 p.m.,"},{"time":313594,"text":"a woman identified as Miranda Brown,"},{"time":315669,"text":"44, of Brooklyn, fell to her death"},{"time":318499,"text":"from the roof of a Manhattan hotel.\""},{"time":320865,"text":"It begins in Elliott's voice,"},{"time":322595,"text":"but then Elliott's voice recedes,"},{"time":324336,"text":"and we hear the voices of Elsa, Margot and Simon,"},{"time":327718,"text":"characters that Elliott created on Twitter"},{"time":330817,"text":"specifically to tell this story,"},{"time":332546,"text":"a story from multiple perspectives"},{"time":335160,"text":"leading up to this moment at 10:13 p.m."},{"time":338285,"text":"when this woman falls to her death."},{"time":340563,"text":"These three characters brought an authentic vision"},{"time":343667,"text":"from multiple perspectives."},{"time":345389,"text":"One reviewer called Elliott's story"},{"time":347715,"text":"\"Twitter fiction done right,\" because she did."},{"time":350605,"text":"She captured that voice"},{"time":352333,"text":"and she had multiple characters and it happened in real time."},{"time":355521,"text":"Interestingly, though, it wasn't just"},{"time":358220,"text":"Twitter as a distribution mechanism."},{"time":360384,"text":"It was also Twitter as a production mechanism."},{"time":362528,"text":"Elliott told me later"},{"time":363772,"text":"she wrote the whole thing with her thumbs."},{"time":367819,"text":"She laid on the couch and just went back and forth"},{"time":371622,"text":"between different characters"},{"time":373471,"text":"tweeting out each line, line by line."},{"time":376084,"text":"I think that this kind of spontaneous creation"},{"time":378837,"text":"of what was coming out of the characters' voices"},{"time":381353,"text":"really lent an authenticity to the characters themselves,"},{"time":384462,"text":"but also to this format that she had created"},{"time":387140,"text":"of multiple perspectives in a single story on Twitter."}]},{"cues":[{"time":391753,"text":"As you begin to play with flexible identity online,"},{"time":394480,"text":"it gets even more interesting"},{"time":395777,"text":"as you start to interact with the real world."},{"time":397722,"text":"Things like Invisible Obama"},{"time":399626,"text":"or the famous \"binders full of women\""},{"time":401867,"text":"that came up during the 2012 election cycle,"},{"time":404413,"text":"or even the fan fiction universe of \"West Wing\" Twitter"},{"time":408584,"text":"in which you have all of these accounts"},{"time":410694,"text":"for every single one of the characters in \"The West Wing,\""},{"time":413670,"text":"including the bird that taps at Josh Lyman's window"},{"time":417573,"text":"in one single episode. (Laughter)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":421709,"text":"All of these are rapid iterations on a theme."},{"time":424845,"text":"They are creative people experimenting"},{"time":427161,"text":"with the bounds of what is possible in this medium."},{"time":430217,"text":"You look at something like \"West Wing\" Twitter,"},{"time":431970,"text":"in which you have these fictional characters"},{"time":434370,"text":"that engage with the real world."},{"time":436328,"text":"They comment on politics,"},{"time":438120,"text":"they cry out against the evils of Congress."},{"time":442654,"text":"Keep in mind, they're all Democrats."},{"time":444438,"text":"And they engage with the real world."},{"time":447758,"text":"They respond to it."},{"time":449616,"text":"So once you take flexible identity,"},{"time":451761,"text":"anonymity, engagement with the real world,"},{"time":454460,"text":"and you move beyond simple homage or parody"},{"time":457631,"text":"and you put these tools to work in telling a story,"},{"time":461220,"text":"that's when things get really interesting."}]},{"cues":[{"time":463103,"text":"So during the Chicago mayoral election"},{"time":465912,"text":"there was a parody account."},{"time":467480,"text":"It was Mayor Emanuel."},{"time":468894,"text":"It gave you everything you wanted from Rahm Emanuel,"},{"time":472360,"text":"particularly in the expletive department."},{"time":475680,"text":"This foul-mouthed account"},{"time":477759,"text":"followed the daily activities of the race,"},{"time":481646,"text":"providing commentary as it went."},{"time":483326,"text":"It followed all of the natural tropes"},{"time":485807,"text":"of a good, solid Twitter parody account,"},{"time":488189,"text":"but then started to get weird."},{"time":491871,"text":"And as it progressed, it moved from this commentary"},{"time":495244,"text":"to a multi-week, real-time science fiction epic"},{"time":500512,"text":"in which your protagonist, Rahm Emanuel,"},{"time":503600,"text":"engages in multi-dimensional travel on election day,"},{"time":507757,"text":"which is -- it didn't actually happen."},{"time":510370,"text":"I double checked the newspapers."}]},{"cues":[{"time":513788,"text":"And then, very interestingly, it came to an end."},{"time":517331,"text":"This is something that doesn't usually happen"},{"time":519330,"text":"with a Twitter parody account."},{"time":520791,"text":"It ended, a true narrative conclusion."},{"time":524520,"text":"And so the author, Dan Sinker, who was a journalist,"},{"time":527742,"text":"who was completely anonymous this whole time,"},{"time":530077,"text":"I think Dan -- it made a lot of sense for him"},{"time":533775,"text":"to turn this into a book,"},{"time":535359,"text":"because it was a narrative format in the end,"},{"time":538732,"text":"and I think that turning it into a book"},{"time":541293,"text":"is representative of this idea that he had created something new"},{"time":544991,"text":"that needed to be translated into previous formats."}]},{"cues":[{"time":548617,"text":"One of my favorite examples"},{"time":550710,"text":"of something that's happening on Twitter right now,"},{"time":552706,"text":"actually, is the very absurdist Crimer Show."},{"time":557482,"text":"Crimer Show tells the story"},{"time":559914,"text":"of a supercriminal and a hapless detective"},{"time":562655,"text":"that face off in this exceptionally strange lingo,"},{"time":566340,"text":"with all of the tropes of a television show."},{"time":568762,"text":"Crimer Show's creator has said that"},{"time":570299,"text":"it is a parody of a popular type of show in the U.K.,"},{"time":575291,"text":"but, man, is it weird."},{"time":578149,"text":"And there are all these times where Crimer,"},{"time":580120,"text":"the supercriminal, does all of these TV things."},{"time":582549,"text":"He's always taking off his sunglasses"},{"time":584801,"text":"or turning to the camera,"},{"time":587769,"text":"but these things just happen in text."},{"time":590209,"text":"I think borrowing all of these tropes from television"},{"time":593043,"text":"and additionally presenting each Crimer Show"},{"time":596795,"text":"as an episode, spelled E-P-P-A-S-O-D, \"eppasod,\""},{"time":602028,"text":"presenting them as episodes"},{"time":604077,"text":"really, it creates something new."},{"time":607107,"text":"There is a new \"eppasod\" of Crimer Show"},{"time":610696,"text":"on Twitter pretty much every day,"},{"time":612820,"text":"and they're archived that way."},{"time":614432,"text":"And I think this is an interesting experiment in format."},{"time":617213,"text":"Something totally new has been created here"},{"time":619497,"text":"out of parodying something on television."}]},{"cues":[{"time":623033,"text":"I think in nonfiction real-time storytelling,"},{"time":625873,"text":"there are a lot of really excellent examples as well."},{"time":628640,"text":"RealTimeWWII is an account"},{"time":630589,"text":"that documents what was happening on this day 60 years ago"},{"time":634652,"text":"in exceptional detail, as if"},{"time":637021,"text":"you were reading the news reports from that day."},{"time":639750,"text":"And the author Teju Cole has done"},{"time":641505,"text":"a lot of experimentation with putting a literary twist"},{"time":644916,"text":"on events of the news."},{"time":646544,"text":"In this particular case, he's talking about drone strikes."},{"time":650987,"text":"I think that in both of these examples,"},{"time":653587,"text":"you're beginning to see ways in which"},{"time":655228,"text":"people are telling stories with nonfiction content"},{"time":658052,"text":"that can be built into new types"},{"time":660961,"text":"of fictional storytelling."}]},{"cues":[{"time":663522,"text":"So with real-time storytelling,"},{"time":666084,"text":"blurring the lines between fact and fiction,"},{"time":668613,"text":"the real world and the digital world,"},{"time":670690,"text":"flexible identity, anonymity,"},{"time":674472,"text":"these are all tools that we have accessible to us,"},{"time":677993,"text":"and I think that they're just the building blocks."},{"time":679885,"text":"They are the bits that we use"},{"time":682523,"text":"to create the structures, the frames,"},{"time":685160,"text":"that then become our settlements on this"},{"time":688258,"text":"wide open frontier for creative experimentation."}]},{"cues":[{"time":691018,"text":"Thank you."}]},{"cues":[{"time":692469,"text":"(Applause)"}]}]}